07:26.172 --> 07:48.653
Now you've heard my story about a place I know down in Tennessee where the tall corn grows Hidden from the world in a bunch of fines 
Where the moon's a little bashful and it seldom shines Civilized people live there, all right But they all go native on a Saturday night Thank you, Charlie, thank you.

07:49.696 --> 07:54.541
Friends, I wanted to tell you about a little incident that happened to me here not too long ago.

07:55.242 --> 07:57.764
The boys had been fighting fire there night and day.

07:58.425 --> 08:00.407
And I do mean night and day.

08:00.427 --> 08:02.790
When night comes, that don't mean a thing to these boys.

08:02.990 --> 08:06.514
As long as the fire's going, they got to keep going too.

08:06.534 --> 08:10.518
So they needed food and they needed water and all that sort of stuff.

08:10.558 --> 08:19.247
So me and one of the fire bosses run up to the Crossroads Country Store there to get something to eat for these boys and some water and stuff.

08:19.885 --> 08:46.753
Well, we got up to the Crossroads store and had the radio going there full blast, so I stayed with the radio to see if a message come in for us, 
and he went in the store to buy the stuff that we needed, something to eat and all that sort of stuff, one of them hardware lunches, you know, 
sardines and crackers and stuff, and there was several fellas around, there's right there at the Crossroads, and there were several fellas standing around, and

08:46.953 --> 08:49.077
And these guys began to gather around.

08:49.137 --> 08:54.647
First one come over there and leaned over in the door, and he was listening, and then another, and another.

08:54.687 --> 08:58.113
And first thing you know, they was all over there listening to this radio.

08:58.574 --> 09:04.685
Well, it was interesting because these fellows had never heard of, much less heard.

09:05.025 --> 09:06.788
They didn't know such a thing existed.

09:07.149 --> 09:10.615
They didn't have any idea that the forestry boys had...

09:10.595 --> 09:33.598
occasions of this kind now they knew the fire was raging because they could see the smoke and they all gathered up around the car yes sir it was a lot of fun to them local people until the fire patrol plane came over and it was right over the fire circling we could see the plane and this is what they heard the pilot say air patrol plane number three to fire dispatcher

09:34.118 --> 09:36.461
Tom, you've got to get more men out on this fire.

09:36.722 --> 09:40.887
She's really rolling and the wind's changed and driving the fire right into the game preserve.

09:41.849 --> 09:44.552
On the north side, there's a break over into that logging area.

09:44.933 --> 09:47.176
Those logs are still on the ground.

09:47.196 --> 09:50.701
I tell you, Tom, we're not going to lick this fire with the number of men on it now.

09:51.101 --> 09:53.605
You've just got to get more men in on it.

09:53.625 --> 09:57.670
Well, sir, you never saw such a change come over people's face in your life.

09:58.651 --> 10:00.514
Really, friends, I wish you could have seen it.

10:01.085 --> 10:07.034
Now, you're talking about a bunch of faces that got solemn and got down to business all of a sudden.

10:07.054 --> 10:07.876
These fellows did.

10:07.936 --> 10:12.623
I couldn't help but notice I was watching all of them because I'm really interested in this thing.

10:13.024 --> 10:14.025
There was no joking.

10:14.947 --> 10:16.389
There was nothing said.

10:16.529 --> 10:20.335
In fact, everybody just quieted down there all of a sudden.

10:20.355 --> 10:24.662
And for the first time, these men knew what forest fires was all about.

10:25.452 --> 10:28.541
It was their game that these boys was protecting.

10:28.762 --> 10:33.256
It was their game that was in danger, and it was their jobs that could be lost.

10:33.276 --> 10:36.947
And when the fireballs came out of the store, friend, what do you think he said?

10:37.383 --> 10:44.932
He found a bunch of these men, in fact, all of them, was loaded up in the back of the truck, and they was ready to go with us right back to the fire.

10:44.952 --> 10:48.376
They wanted to go out and help, and that's exactly what they done.

10:48.396 --> 10:51.120
And that's what I call real cooperation.

10:51.460 --> 10:56.566
Now, here we go with the next tune, and I believe it features Herman on his little guitar here.

10:56.686 --> 11:04.936
Ethiopian, steam-heated, butane-burning steel guitar with a little dab-dab and half two dabs of the panhandle rag.

11:04.956 --> 11:07.339
On board, ballpoint sound.

11:08.197 --> 11:35.807
Well, what's the matter with your toy?

11:44.056 --> 11:50.491
I must go, son.

11:50.832 --> 12:00.073
I must stop them.

12:21.670 --> 12:22.692
Well, thank you, Herman.

12:22.732 --> 12:23.333
Thank you a lot.

12:23.353 --> 12:25.155
That was very nicely done there, my boy.

12:25.756 --> 12:26.978
Not near as good as I could have done.

12:27.339 --> 12:28.080
Friends, we've got to go.

12:28.100 --> 12:28.981
We've run out of time.

12:29.001 --> 12:34.310
But before we go, here's just a little thought that I'd like to leave with you, and I do hope you'll keep it in mind.

12:35.331 --> 12:40.019
The forester has a mighty tough job, fighting fire, protecting your land.

12:40.820 --> 12:46.108
So please keep in mind that oftentimes he would sure love your helping hand.

12:46.460 --> 13:02.157
Friends, we've sure enjoyed this little visit here with you under the old pine tree.

13:02.440 --> 13:04.803
and we do hope that you've enjoyed it too.

13:04.823 --> 13:06.586
We'll be coming your way again soon.

